  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening institutional Disaster Preparedness and community level Epidemic Preparedness in Western Region, Uganda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Enhance district level capacities by providing support in the development and operationalization of multi-hazard district contingency plans, improving EW systems and enhancing surge capacity.
2. Integrate Forecast-based Action into DCPs
3. Strengthen community-level epidemic preparedness by enhancing surveillance and referral systems to ensure early detection and response regarding diseases / events of public health concern.
4. Advocate for a National Disaster Preparedness and Management Law that incorporates anticipatory funding principles.
5. Ensure protection mainstreaming in all elements by enhancing responders&apos; capacity on protection and accountability towards the population and the adaptation of protection into EW/EA mechanism.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">11,864 local populations in the area. 
5,000  displaced people</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Action targets distrits that are exposed to multiple hazards and are accepting new refugees, or are transit areas:
* Kisoro
* Ntoroko
* Kanungu
* Kasese
* Isingiro
* Kamwenge
* Kyegegwa
* Kikuube</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Action will strengthen the capacities of District Disaster Management Committees, District Task Forces and their local structures to establish well-functioning multi-hazard preparedness and response systems to ensure Early Warning and Early Action.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">There is a clear need to strengthen DRM in Uganda to address the multiplicity of crises including epidemics, new refugee influxes and natural hazards. The most common and frequent hazards include floods, landslides, drought, earthquakes,
hailstorms and windstorms. Since 2017, Uganda has experienced an influx of refugees from South Sudan and DRC and is now hosting 1,4 million refugees. In the coming time UNHCR predicts a large influx of refugees into the country. The scale of the refugee crisis continues to overwhelm national and local capacities. Active cross border movement combined with porous borders increases the risk of importation of epidemics (e.g. EVD). Besides, communities are often affected by Cholera, Typhoid Fever, Malaria and Diarrhoea. The COVID-19 global pandemic is widespread and is strongly impacting
the health system, economy, livelihoods and protection.</narrative>
  </description>
